description.text: I wasn't content with the moderate peril I subjected my iPhone to with the iPhone Mixer Attachment (thing 18929), so I thought I'd step things up a bit with this beauty. I've heard lots of people extol the virtues of glass as a build platform, so this seems like a natural use for an iPhone 4. This iPhone holder is designed to replace the heated build platform on a MakerBot Thing-o-Matic. The four sections fit together using dovetails and once the phone is in place, the platform is quite solid. The phone will fit face-up or face-down. There is no provision for heating the build platform, so it probably will work best with PLA. Created for the Absurd iPhone Accessory contest sponsored by EngineerVsDesigner (EvD) and Makerbot Industries. The parametric OpenSCAD file relies on sorup's iPhone4 model (thing 12879) for various constants, but does not use the model itself. It also relies on jag's dovetail module (thing 10269). A few more pictures are on flickr: http://www.flickr.com/photos/bradandkathy/sets/72157629259233290/
Print the four sections and assemble. Mount using M3x20 screws and nuts. Level & start printing!

description.text:
Almost all the holders I see here don't press the glass plate against the base but press the glass side against a flat surface or the end of a screw causing the glass plate to lift ! At least a slanted surface should be used !
Good luck for bed levelling and issues due to thermal expansion with heated bed.

The paper clips are a good solution but interfere, are bulky and don't look professional.
I did these in a few minutes using 1mm spring steel wire. Can be a tad bigger. Just to give an idea.
They press the glass plate tight and will allow thermal expansion. It articulates on the bed adjusting screws. Make two for left two for right.
Flat steel shim as used to hold the glass in picture frame would do too. Just find the right size and modify it if required.

Note this thing: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1947870 does the job as well (holds tight and allow easy installation) and doesn't require the tools and the skill to bend, cut steel wire or shim (don't expect cheap Chinese pliers to cut spring wire.)

PS: The stl is just there because an stl file is required !

WARNING: Tempered steel wire and steel shim when cut can send pieces flying, produce sharp edges that can lead to injury to the eyes or make you bleed ! Too much bleeding will cause DEATH. Proceed at your own risk. :)

description.text:
UPDATE 20.2.2017:
PLEASE USE THE NEW IMPROVED VERSION!
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2122573

This is an extremely simple, yet very efficient adapter for filament spools which I made for the spool holder that came with my Anet A8. It will move very smoothly with just the M8 rod that the holder came with, no bearings necessary. It will work on any spool holer using an M8 rod.

I used all the inner spool diameters that I have stumbled across so far for this adapter, so it should fit quite a few different brands of filament spools.

Print two of these adapters and install them on the M8 rod that came with your spool holder. The minimum you need is two M8 nuts, one on each outer side of the adapter with the filament spool inbetween the two adapters. But I recommend you add two lock nuts to one end of the rod with a little space inbetween as a guide to keep the rod from drifting towards either side (see photo). And if you use a winged or knurled nut on the opposite side (not visible in the picture), changing spools will be much quicker, but a regular nut will work just as well.

title: Big Dog feeder with Nema 17 , arduino, stepper, servo, driver, rtc, pvc

description.text:
This is my open project of big dog feeding system.

Parts involved :

  • 1x PVC T joint element with 48mm inside diameter & 66mm outside diameter.
  • 1x Nema 17 stepper motor.
  • 1x Arduino Uno board
  • 1x RTC time like DS3231, but can use as well DS1307 or others, to keep accurate timing for years to come :), and avoid Arduino rollover of variables for time

  • 1x Stepper Driver. I used UI robot driver model : UIM24002 .. but you can use any other type as long as it is at least 1.6A for the most common Nema17 motor.

  • 1x 3d printed Augere that is attached here, to fit inside the Pvc T joint.

  • 1x 3d printed Pcv lid and Nema 17 motor support.

  • 1x M4 nut & bolt
  • 3x small fixation screw like M3's to fix the holder of motor on the pvc pipe

The program to feed the dog at 3 time intervals is placed in the attached zip.
Movies can be seen as well here :

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hEsPlHfDCFU
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5a9XasnpnV4

If inventor drawings are required please request them.. trough messages.. and as well drawings of the complete enclosure..
This is still in work. Currently I'm attaching a servo to steer the food before moving it out as otherwise it would block.. and it really works as you can see in the last clip movie.

I scaled all files 200%, somehow scale got messed up.
If i will print another one i will print the buttons with 0.25mm nozzle, they are just to small to print accurately - they turned out semi-acceptable, though.
I printed faces with two layers, on 0.4mm i switched from black to white, that gave the eyes and mouth some depth - first i printed them all white and all you could hardly notice the features, this way with two colors it looks really cool
I will post the corrected body mesh, it has some weird points sticking out from the back and when you try to print it first layer is just four small points..
I will enlarge the small two buttons - they are tiny to print..

Anyway - if you put some effort into cleaning the little pieces (10 minutes of work) he will turn out great!

2016-12-14
I updated the STL files, body has modified back so it prints nicely. I enlarged the details on his back a bit, and enlarged two small buttons (triangle and small round one) so they print better..
I have one sitting on my monitor and one dangling in my car from a rear view mirror - I just drilled a hole (two holes at 45degree angle actually) on top of the body for cord to hang him from.

comments.text: I also struggled with the Z axis nut alignment. I assembled my bed to the bearing brackets and made sure the whole assembly moves up and down smoothly. I then mounted the Z stepper motor with lead screw and nut at the bottom of the travel. I let the position of the motor place where the bracket attaches to the cross member. If the cross member is too far away I suggest that you use shims rather than trying to move it which would lose the flatness of the bed support achieved by assembling it on a flat surface. I ended up shimming my bracket to make it more level to the bed. Once you get the motor and lead screw properly centered and attached to the bed, it should move smoothly all the way to the top of the travel. This is a parametric design for a Pottery wheel head. The smaller sizes can be used for banding wheels, or any other kind of revolving platform.

A plastic version isn't durable enough for pottery, so I've used the 3d printed wheel as a pattern for sand casting of metal. In this case I made the wheel from Aluminum.

For the CAD I have used Python Code to generate OpenSCAD code which can then output an STL file.

The larger wheels are bigger than my printer can handle so I have an option to print the wheel in pie segments which can be glued together.

I also have a core box model. A core is needed to prevent metal shrinkage in the central hub when the wheel is being cast.

The Python source files can be found here:
https://github.com/deadsy/parametric_cad/tree/master/wheel

The files attached to this thing are specific instances of the OpenSCAD and STL output for an 8" wheel.

I don't expect too many people to cast their own wheels based on this pattern, but if you are interested, grab the Python code from github and play around with the parameters to make the kind of wheel you want.

title: Leica ABLON style film leader trimming guide.
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This film leader trimming guide is my take on the original Leica ABLON metal version. Old bottom loading Leicas need a much longer film leader than is cut into modern 35mm film, the guide helps to get the right shape to prevent things going awry in your camera.

Some people will sneer and say "just use scissors/teeth/bayonet and guess the shape", others will say "don't bother, just load your film without the longer leader, stuff your fingers in through the shutter opening and wrangle your film into place".

To those people I say if you're happy doing it that way, great, carry on. It's just not my bag, man. And if Oskar Barnack wants a long neat leader, that is what he shall get. :)

While the originals are still available on a certain auction site, they are somewhat expensive. One of the joys/perils of Leica ownership I guess, the stuff is nice, but pricey.

So, as I have a CAD package and a 3D printer I decided to make myself one (and share it with the Thingiverse community). All I ask is that you don't make them to sell for profit. This is a non-commercial design for your personal use.

Feel free to tag me in your Instagram pics if you post any of your trimming guide, you'll find me as "@PariahPics" on there. I hope it helps you load your Barnack Leica with ease. Be sure to look at the Post-Printing section for further info.

Printer Brand:

CEL

Printer:

Robox

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

10%-100% it's up to you

Notes:

The footprint of the model is 135 x 88mm so should fit nicely on most printers.

Refinement & finishing.

Once it has printed you may find that you need to clean a few things up (depending upon your printer resolution). The small lugs that hold the film in place usually need filing slightly on the sides, as do the ends of the hinge cylinders, so that the two halves sit neatly together.

Speaking of the hinge, you may also need to use a small drill bit to open up the printed bores to accept your hinge pin (which I made from some 1.6mm stainless welding rod cut to 105mm long).

The curved edge (that you run your blade along when trimming your film) can be lightly filed/sanded to remove any printing burrs. Ideally this should be done when the two parts are mated together so that the curve remains the same. It's not crucial though.

Once you've positioned the film into the holder you can either trim it down on a flat surface (probably with a cutting mat beneath) or hold it in your hand (keeping your fingers well away from the edge that you'll be trimming along) and use an X-Acto pointed blade to follow the guide edge. Don't press too hard against your printed guide, the aim is to smoothly trim the film, not gouge out the guiding edge.

Make sure that your trimmed edge of film doesn't have any nicks or splits that could cause a tear when winding on the film once it's in your camera. The idea of this guide is to help you get a nice neat and rounded leader onto your film without cutting through a sprocket hole.

DISCLAIMER Use blades with caution. I cannot be held responsible for you slicing off the ends of your fingers whist using this guide!

title: 13" Dust collector Blower Fan Assembly
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
My Uncle made a large dust collector for his shop but he kept having problems with the fan assembly he made out of wood. He said he had balance issues and his fan assemblies would not last long. I figured I would take on the challenge of trying to make a fan assembly that would be well balanced and suite his purpose.
I first made the whole fan assembly in one .stl file. 13" was way too large for my print bed but I thought maybe I could use one of those online printing services. Nope, they wanted about $2K for it. So, I redesigned it to be printed in smaller pieces and then glued together. All the pieces will fit on a 230 x 150 x 150 mm build platform. I did include the original full fan if someone has a huge build plate and ton of time to print it.
The fan is designed to be mounted on a 5/8ths shaft. There are two different versions of the center shaft that holds the blades, one with 8 blades and one with 16 blades. I printed the 8 blade version mainly because the blades take about 3 hours and some change to print. The whole thing took me about 48 hours to print. After printing do a dry fit of all the pieces to ensure they fit well, the blades fit very tightly into the center shaft, and then glue them all together.
I don't know how useful this would be to anyone else but I thought I would share it with the community just for fun. Enjoy!

description.text:
Based on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:697672 originally made by by jsc,.

The scraper above was a nice good looking scraper that used razor blades but once i printed had two issues.
The blade holder was hold only by friction
and the cap was over-enginnered too tight to put. The cup was way more secure than the blade.
So i decided to make some changes.

This scraper uses two M2.5 bolts 5mm long (4mm long should fit better) and two M2.5 nuts.
In this version the blade is fixed securely with screws and the cup is holded by friction.

In order to print this item you need to print
1) scraper.stl (modded with M2.5 screws and nuts)
2) lid.st (same as the original)
3) scrapercup.stl (new simplified lid cup)

I include all the files even the sources so you can re modify this item at your needs.

This is how to create a concrete lamp for your house or office, that give a nice retro and industrial style to your desk.

1) Download and 3d print the mold (You don't need a good quality of printing)

1bis) Assembly the mold (2 parts together)

2) Prepare concrete powder and mix it with water inside a small (Old) Glass in order to have a mixture not so liquid and not so hard (Just the perfect mix, up to you).

3) Fill the mold and wait 1 week (Inside house in order to be up to 0°C)

4) Unmould, and clean the sides of the part with sandpaper.

5) ASSEMBLY

You will need :

  • A retro light bulb (Mount M24)

  • A M24 mount

  • An electric cable with a On/Off switch

6) ENJOY and show your artistic side to your friends and colleagues because, you did it by yourself ! (Congratulation)
